04834nam a22007695i 9780823284092DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232840927 a10.1515/97808232840922doi  a(DE-B1597)555309  a(OCoLC)1090540080  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0671102bisacsh04a230.0922231 aRose, Marika, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Theology of Failure :bŽižek against Christian Innocence /cMarika Rose. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: failing -- t1. Ontology and desire in dionysius the areopagite -- t2. Apophatic theology and its vicissitudes -- t3. The death drive: from Freud to žižek -- t4. The gift and violence -- t5. Divine violence as trauma -- t6. Mystical theology and the four discourses -- tConclusion: theology as failure -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEveryone agrees that theology has failed; but the question of how to understand and respond to this failure is complex and contested. Against both the radical orthodox attempt to return to a time before the theology’s failure and the deconstructive theological attempt to open theology up to the hope of a future beyond failure, Rose proposes an account of Christian identity as constituted by, not despite, failure. Understanding failure as central to theology opens up new possibilities for confronting Christianity’s violent and kyriarchal history and abandoning the attempt to discover a pure Christ outside of the grotesque materiality of the church.The Christian mystical tradition begins with Dionysius the Areopagite’s uncomfortable but productive conjunction of Christian theology and Neoplatonism. The tensions generated by this are central to Dionysius’s legacy, visible not only in subsequent theological thought but also in much twentieth century continental philosophy as it seeks to disentangle itself from its Christian ancestry. A Theology of Failure shows how the work of Slavoj Žižek represents an attempt to repeat the original move of Christian mystical theology, bringing together the themes of language, desire, and transcendence not with Neoplatonism but with a materialist account of the world. Tracing these themes through the work of Dionysius and Derrida and through contemporary debates about the gift, violence, and revolution, this book offers a critical theological engagement with Žižek's account of social and political transformation, showing how Žižek's work makes possible a materialist reading of apophatic theology and Christian identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMysticism. 0aPhilosophical theology. 0aPostmodernism. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Systematic.2bisacsh  aApophaticism.  aContinental Philosophy of Religion.  aContinental Pholosophy.  aMystical Theology.  aNegative Theology.  aPseudo-Dionysius.  aRadical Theology.  aSlavoj Zizek.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072273440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823284092zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823284092423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823284092/original  a978-3-11-072273-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruy